Supplemental materials to ‘POnSS: efficient and accurate annotation’

Joe Rodd

Analysis 0: Simulations of conventional coefficients of reliability

We started with the dataset of word annotations segmented by the baseline method. For each individual word token, the median word onset time across all annotators was calculated. The same was done for the offset times. For each segmentation, the difference between the segmented onset and offset times and the median onset and offset times was calculated. The distribution of these divergence times is shown in panel 1 of Figure S1. The other distributions in Figure S1 show the same data, but with some segmentations replaced by times sampled from a predefined normal distribution. The \(\sigma\) parameter of that distribution was varied between 0 and 100 ms, as was the proportion of items replaced. This is indicated in the labels above each distribution. If the re-sampling distribution had low \(\sigma\), then the distribution becomes ‘tighter’, for instance in distribution 5, where nearly all the probability mass falls within the green region, which indicates times between -5 ms and 5 ms around the median segmentation. If the re-sampling distribution had a higher \(\sigma\), then the distribution widens.

We subsequently calculated the Krippendorff’s alpha for the matrices underlying the distributions in Figure S1 (and many others, such that we had near-continuous variation in the two parameters of the re-sampling). Figure S2 shows the variation in Krippendorf’s alpha as a factor of the sigma of the re-sampling distribution and the percentage of the original matrix replaced. All the alpha values obtained were strikingly close to 1.0, which would conventionally be interpreted as indicating near perfect reliability. Furthermore, distributions that are quite different in their shape under visual inspection, such as distributions 11 and 13 or 1 and 5 in Figure S1, received the same alpha. When, rather than normalising the data by subtracting the median of the row, alpha is calculated on the raw boundary times, the reported reliability was very close to 0. Figure S3 is a version of Figure S2 for ICC, which has essentially the same distribution as Krippendorff’s alpha.

Figure S4 shows, in two panels, the variation in percentage agreement, with a tolerance of 10 ms or 20 ms, respectively. Again, the useful variation is limited, though very good performance is better distinguished, for instance between distributions 1 and 5. Percentage agreement is, unsurprisingly poor at distinguishing less good distributions, for instance 20 and 21, which achieve close to 0% agreement.

From these simulations, we conclude that none of Krippendorff’s alpha, ICC or percentage agreement offers a sufficiently sensitive way to assess the reliability of speech segmentation data, that can differentiate between samples of both well-segmented and poorly-segmented speech data.

Particle swarm optimisation

We construct subsets of the test dataset, that varied in the proportion of each condition (speaking rate, task) represented. For the rate conditions, we set the proportions of each rate to approximately 10% to approximately 80%, in steps of 10%. For the task conditions, we set the proportions of manual annotation to between 20% and 80%, again in steps of 10%. The different levels were exhaustively combined, meaning that 252 samples were constructed.

sample_optimisations <- bind_rows(lapply(list.files("grid_results","sample_optimisations\\d+"),function(x){readRDS(paste0("grid_results/",x))}))

sample_optimisations <- sample_optimisations %>% mutate(weight = 1-KL)

calculate_thetas <- function(thetaA,thetaB){
  list(theta1 = thetaA,
       theta2 = ((1 - thetaA) * thetaB),
       theta3 = 1 - (thetaA + ((1 - thetaA) * thetaB)))
}

sample_optimisations$theta1 <- calculate_thetas(sample_optimisations$thetaA,sample_optimisations$thetaB)$theta1
sample_optimisations$theta2 <- calculate_thetas(sample_optimisations$thetaA,sample_optimisations$thetaB)$theta2
sample_optimisations$theta3 <- calculate_thetas(sample_optimisations$thetaA,sample_optimisations$thetaB)$theta3

long_sample_optimisations <- left_join(sample_optimisations %>% select(realised_456,realised_646,realised_915,realised_manual,realised_POnSS,weight,sigma1,sigma2,sigma3) %>% gather("distribution","sigmavalue",sigma1,sigma2,sigma3) %>% mutate(distribution=recode(distribution,sigma1="narrow",sigma2="medium",sigma3="wide")),
                                       sample_optimisations %>% select(realised_456,realised_646,realised_915,realised_manual,realised_POnSS,weight,theta1,theta2,theta3) %>% gather("distribution","thetavalue",theta1,theta2,theta3) %>% mutate(distribution=recode(distribution,theta1="narrow",theta2="medium",theta3="wide")))

long_sample_optimisations$weight_theta <- long_sample_optimisations$weight * long_sample_optimisations$thetavalue

long_sample_optimisations$distribution <- as.factor(long_sample_optimisations$distribution)
long_sample_optimisations$distribution <- relevel(long_sample_optimisations$distribution,"medium")
contrasts(long_sample_optimisations$distribution) <- contr.sum(3)

hydro_fit_plot

Figure S6 An example of the optimised mixture-model fit (orange) to the observed distribution of one of the samples (black line)

We then used PSO to parametrically fit the distributions in each subset, with KL as score function.

Boundaries were set for the space to be searched by PSO. These boundaries are set to ensure that one distribution fits the tight peak, a second distribution fits the shoulders, and the third fits the tails, though they overlap enough that if the model decided to, it could reject our ordering. The thetas are parmeterised such that the first (thetaA) decides the proportion of the first distribution vs the second and third together. The second theta parameter (thetaB) decides the proportion of the second distribution vs the third distribution, within what is left over after thetaA. This way, it is unnecessaary to code the constraint that the three resulting thetas should sum to 1.0.

This analysis is available in optimize_PSO.R.

Inferential model (model 1)

We fitted an inferential model over the sigma values identified by PSO, to examine what the impact of the different rate conditions and the task was on the fitted sigmas.

f_sigma_reliability <- bf(sigmavalue|weights(weight_theta) ~ 1 + realised_POnSS*distribution+realised_456*distribution+realised_915*distribution,
                    sigma~distribution,
                    nu~distribution,
                    family="student")


m_sigma_reliability <- brm(f_sigma_reliability,
    data  = long_sample_optimisations,
    prior = c(prior(normal(0,5),class="b")),
    file="model_fits/m_sigma_reliability",
    chains = 6,
    cores = 2,
    iter=8000
    )
fes_sigma_reliability <- summary(m_sigma_reliability)$fixed

pp_data <- function (object, type, nsamples, group = NULL, x = NULL, newdata = NULL, 
          resp = NULL, subset = NULL, ...) 
{
  y <- brms:::get_y(object, resp = resp, newdata = object$data)
  subset <- brms:::subset_samples(object, NULL, 5)
  pred_args <- list(object, newdata = object$data, resp = NULL, 
                    subset = subset, sort = FALSE, summary = FALSE)
  yrep <- do_call("predict", pred_args)
  
  return(list(y=y,
              yrep=yrep))
}

Analysis 2: Speed of methods

Simple resampling to get 1000 annotations

The following plot compares the time taken to have 5000 annotated words by the manual method, and by using POnSS. It is much quicker to use POnSS (excluding set up time).

Around 5 percent of word candidates are ultimately rejected (don’t make it into the finished dataset).

manual_annotations <- readRDS("manual_annotations.RDS")

if(!file.exists("time_investment_draws.rds")){
  draw_manual <- function(draw){
  set.seed(456+draw)
  e <- manual_annotations %>% sample_n(5000) %>% summarise(total_time_investment = as.numeric(lubridate::dseconds(as.numeric(sum(busy_with_word,na.rm = T)))))
  e
}


 draw_distributed <- function(draw){
  good_words_count <- 0
  attempt = 5000
  while(good_words_count != 5000) {
    if( 5000 - good_words_count > 100){
      attempt = attempt + 50
    } else if(5000 - good_words_count > 0){
      attempt = attempt + 1
    } else if(5000 - good_words_count < -100){
      attempt = attempt - 50
    } else if(5000 - good_words_count < 0){
      attempt = attempt - 1
    }
    set.seed(456+draw)
    e = durations_distributed %>% filter(total_busy_seconds_evaluation < quantile(total_busy_seconds_evaluation,0.99,na.rm = T),
                                           total_busy_seconds_retrimming < quantile(total_busy_seconds_retrimming,0.99,na.rm = T)) %>% sample_n(attempt)
    good_words_count <- nrow(e %>% filter(result_id %in% pincer_durations$word_id))
  }
  
  f <- e %>% summarise(total_time_investment = as.numeric(lubridate::dseconds(sum(total_busy_seconds_evaluation,na.rm = T)+sum(total_busy_seconds_retrimming,na.rm = T))),
                       words_included_in_sample = n(),
                       bad_proportion = 1 - 5000 / words_included_in_sample)
  f
 }
 

time_investment_draws <- data.frame(draw = seq(1,1000)) %>% group_by(draw) %>%
  do({manual_draw = draw_manual(.$draw)
  POnSS_draw = draw_distributed(.$draw)
  data.frame(task = c("manual","POnSS"), total_time_investment = c(manual_draw$total_time_investment,POnSS_draw$total_time_investment),
             POnSS_bad_proportion = c(NA,POnSS_draw$bad_proportion))})

saveRDS(time_investment_draws,file="time_investment_draws.rds")
} else {
  time_investment_draws <- readRDS(file="time_investment_draws.rds")
}

time_investment_draws$task <- as.factor(time_investment_draws$task)
time_investment_draws$time_investment <- time_investment_draws$total_time_investment/60/60

contrasts(time_investment_draws$task) <- contr.sum(2)

time_investment_draws %>% ggplot()+
  geom_density(aes(x=POnSS_bad_proportion,fill=task,colour=task),alpha=0.7)+
  scale_fill_manual(guide=F, values = c("POnSS"="#008FC1","manual" = "#EEA300"))+
  scale_colour_manual(guide=F, values = c("POnSS"="#008FC1","manual" = "#EEA300"))

m_speed <- brm(
  scale(time_investment) ~ 1 + task,
  data = time_investment_draws,
  prior = c(prior(normal(0,1),class="b")),
  chains = 6,
  cores = 3,
  iter=8000,
  file="model_fits/m_speed",
  family="gaussian",
  sample_prior = T)
